body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Yosys (81876a37) does not support passing real values as parameters to modules and doing math operations on them.

An example use case of that is a counter that generates a divided clock with duty cycle specified as a real number. Another use case is eg. calculation of PLL dividers given desired clock frequencies.

Consider the following design:

```
`timescale 1ns/10ps

module counter (
  input  wire CLK,
  output wire O
);
  parameter MAX = 100;
  parameter real DUTY = 0.5;

  localparam MATCH = $rtoi(MAX * DUTY);

  initial begin
    $display("MAX:   %d", MAX);
    $display("DUTY:  %f", DUTY);
    $display("MATCH: %d", MATCH);
  end

  reg [31:0] cnt;
  initial cnt <= 0;

  always @(posedge CLK)
    if (cnt == (MAX-1))
      cnt <= 0;
    else
      cnt <= cnt + 1;

  assign O = (cnt < MATCH);

endmodule

module top(
);
  reg CLK;

  initial CLK <= 0;
  always #0.5 CLK <= !CLK;

  counter #
  (
    .MAX(100),
    .DUTY(0.75)
  )
  my_counter
  (
    .CLK(CLK),
    .O()
  );

endmodule
```

Here we have a counter with `MAX` and `DUTY` parameters. The `MAX` parameter specifies its counting range while the `DUTY` specifies output duty cycle as a fraction of the `MAX`. It is gives as a real number.

Simulation of the design should yield in a 75% duty cycle square wave signal at the `my_counter.O` pin with the frequency 100 times lower than the input `CLK`.

The design successfully simulates with the XSim (Vivado) and the `$display` statements produce the following output:
```
MAX:           100
DUTY:  0.750000
MATCH:          75
```

The simulation succeeded in the Icarus Verilog too with the identical output of the `$display` statements.

## Expected behavior

The real value of the parameter is accepted and used in calculation of the value of the `MATCH` localparam.

## Actual behavior

Yosys fails on the `read_verilog -pwires design.v` command with:
```
design.v:15: ERROR: System task `$display' called with invalid/unsupported format specifier
```

Even when the `initial` block with `$display` directives is commented out it fails with:
```
design.v:9: ERROR: Parameter `\DUTY' with non-constant value!
```

